We need to construct a new homotopy operator such that h' \mathbin {\circ } h' = 0 and h' \mathbin {\circ } (d_C + \delta _C) \mathbin {\circ } h' = h'. We approach this through a “perturbative” mindset. Starting with h_0 = h, the second equation is off by a difference of h_0 \delta _C h_0. We simply add this as a correction term, h_1 = h_0 + \alpha  h_0 \delta _C h_0 where \alpha  is some coefficient. (Note that essentially the only terms we can consider are of the form h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C \cdots  h_0, since nothing else has the same type.) We still have h_1 \mathbin {\circ } h_1 = 0, and for the second equation this creates a new error term
    \begin {aligned}       &\quad  h_1 (d_C + \delta _C) h_1 - h_1 \\       &= (1 + \alpha ) h_0 \delta _C h_0 + 2 (\alpha  + \alpha ^2) h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 + \alpha ^2 h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0     \end {aligned}
    and we can eliminate the first and second order part by setting \alpha  = -1. The natural next step would be to add a further correction h_2 = h_1 + \beta  h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0. This turns out to require \beta  = +1, and so on.

We need to construct a new homotopy operator such that h' \mathbin {\circ } h' = 0 and h' \mathbin {\circ } (d_C + \delta _C) \mathbin {\circ } h' = h'. We approach this through a “perturbative” mindset. Starting with h_0 = h, the second equation is off by a difference of h_0 \delta _C h_0. We simply add this as a correction term, h_1 = h_0 + \alpha  h_0 \delta _C h_0 where \alpha  is some coefficient. (Note that essentially the only terms we can consider are of the form h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C \cdots  h_0, since nothing else has the same type.) We still have h_1 \mathbin {\circ } h_1 = 0, and for the second equation this creates a new error term
    \begin {aligned}       &\quad  h_1 (d_C + \delta _C) h_1 - h_1 \\       &= (1 + \alpha ) h_0 \delta _C h_0 + 2 (\alpha  + \alpha ^2) h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 + \alpha ^2 h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0     \end {aligned}
    and we can eliminate the first and second order part by setting \alpha  = -1. The natural next step would be to add a further correction h_2 = h_1 + \beta  h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0. This turns out to require \beta  = +1, and so on.

We need to construct a new homotopy operator such that h' \mathbin {\circ } h' = 0 and h' \mathbin {\circ } (d_C + \delta _C) \mathbin {\circ } h' = h'. We approach this through a “perturbative” mindset. Starting with h_0 = h, the second equation is off by a difference of h_0 \delta _C h_0. We simply add this as a correction term, h_1 = h_0 + \alpha  h_0 \delta _C h_0 where \alpha  is some coefficient. (Note that essentially the only terms we can consider are of the form h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C \cdots  h_0, since nothing else has the same type.) We still have h_1 \mathbin {\circ } h_1 = 0, and for the second equation this creates a new error term
    \begin {aligned}       &\quad  h_1 (d_C + \delta _C) h_1 - h_1 \\       &= (1 + \alpha ) h_0 \delta _C h_0 + 2 (\alpha  + \alpha ^2) h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 + \alpha ^2 h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0     \end {aligned}
    and we can eliminate the first and second order part by setting \alpha  = -1. The natural next step would be to add a further correction h_2 = h_1 + \beta  h_0 \delta _C h_0 \delta _C h_0. This turns out to require \beta  = +1, and so on.

A chain reduction consists of maps C_k \mathrel {\smash {\xtofrom [g_k]{f_k}}} D_k such that f_k \mathbin {\circ } g_k = \textrm {id}. Therefore C_\bullet  splits as D_\bullet  \oplus  E_\bullet , and the boundary maps are preserved since f, g are chain maps. We have a homotopy h_k : D_k \oplus  E_k \to  D_{k+1} \oplus  E_{k+1}, which we may write as a (2 \times  2)-matrix. f \mathbin {\circ } h = 0 demands the first row to be zero, and h \mathbin {\circ } g = 0 requires the first column to vanish. This leaves us with
    \begin {bmatrix}       0 & 0 \\       0 & r_k     \end {bmatrix}
    such that r_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } r_k = 0, since h \mathbin {\circ } h = 0.

On the other hand, given only the homotopy operator, we expect to have d \mathbin {\circ } h + h \mathbin {\circ } d = \textrm {id} - g \mathbin {\circ } f. And since g \mathbin {\circ } f should be the projector of C onto the subspace D, \textrm {id} - g \mathbin {\circ } f should be the projector onto E. We are thus led to proving p = d \mathbin {\circ } h + h \mathbin {\circ } d is indeed a projector.
    \begin {aligned}       p_k \mathbin {\circ } p_k &= (d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k) \mathbin {\circ } (d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k) \\       &= d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } \overbrace {h_k \mathbin {\circ } d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k}^{h_k} + d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } \overbrace {h_k \mathbin {\circ } h_{k-1}}^{0} \mathbin {\circ } d_k \\       &\qquad  + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } \underbrace {d_k \mathbin {\circ } d_{k+1}}_{0} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + \underbrace {h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k \mathbin {\circ } h_{k-1}}_{h_{k-1}} \mathbin {\circ } d_k \\       &= d_{k+1} \mathbin {\circ } h_k + h_{k-1} \mathbin {\circ } d_k = p_k.     \end {aligned}
    Therefore we conclude that p_k splits C_k \cong  D_k \oplus  E_k. More over, p \mathbin {\circ } d = d \mathbin {\circ } h \mathbin {\circ } d = d \mathbin {\circ } p, meaning p is a chain map, and therefore the splitting is compatible with the boundary operator. Since h \mathbin {\circ } p = p \mathbin {\circ } h = h \mathbin {\circ } d \mathbin {\circ } h = h, the homotopy is also compatible with the splitting, so we can restrict it onto E_k to get a homotopy from \textrm {id}_E to 0.
